1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. c5 Nc6 $6 {Not the most
accurate move. For Black the best plan is to postpone the typical methods for
counterplay which I'm going to repeat: 1. b6 attacking White's pawn chain 2.
Nc6 preparing e5 at a later moment 3. Ne4 If White takes Black's knight,
obtain counterplay against the "d" pawn; if White doesn't take it, this knight
is very well placed and can be supported by f5. And you already know that
White's plan is to prevent all Black's counterplay and, later on, take
advantage of his queen side majority.} 7. Nf3 (7. Bb5 {Maybe was a little more
accurate. Remember White should wait for Black's Nc6 and then answer with Bb5;
this is a general rule of this variation.}) 7... Ne4 8. Qc2 {Keeping the pawn
structure and attacking the knight on e4; this move is a typical response to
Ne4.} f5 {Blacks using a typical method of counterplay in this line; of course,
this has some inconvenience: 1. leaves the e6 pawn backward; 2. now the e5
square can be used.} 9. Bb5 $1 {Of course it was time.} Bd7 10. O-O Be7 11.
Bxc6 Bxc6 12. b4 {Now White has a typical position. Black has a bishop pair v
the queen side majority and the weaknesses on the "e" file. This determines
White's advantage because Black's bishop pair is temporarily very passive.} O-O
13. Bf4 {Controlling the key e5 square.} g5 14. Be5 $1 f4 15. Nd2 (15. b5 $5 {
Prepares an interesting exchange sacrifice.} Be8 16. Nxe4 dxe4 (16... Bg6 $5
17. Nfd2 dxe4 18. Nxe4 f3 19. Rfe1 {With not enough compensation for Black.}
Qd5 20. Rab1 Bxc5 21. Qxc5 Bxe4 22. Qe7 Rf7 23. Qxg5+ $16) 17. Qxe4 Bxb5 18.
Qxb7 Bxf1 19. Rxf1 $16 {With a clear advantage, because of the more active
play and the passed "c" pawn.}) 15... Nxd2 16. Qxd2 f3 17. g4 $1 {With the
plan of Kh1-Rg1 and Rg3 attacking the weak f3 pawn.} Bf6 18. Bd6 Qd7 19. Kh1 {
Prophylactic move against e5.} Qg7 $6 (19... Rf7 $1) 20. Rad1 (20. Bxf8 $1 Rxf8
21. Rad1 {Black hasn't enough compensation.}) 20... Rf7 21. Rg1 h5 $6 {After
this White's advantage is clear; simply, White's won a pawn.} 22. gxh5 Qh6 23.
Be5 $6 {I will never understand why GM Gdanski failed to push his pawn to b5
instead of this move!} (23. b5 $1) 23... Bxe5 $6 24. Qxg5+ Qxg5 25. Rxg5+ {The
rest is very easy.} Kh7 26. Rxe5 Rg8 27. Rxe6 Rg2 28. b5 Rf5 29. Rg6 Rxf2 30.
Kg1 Rc2 31. bxc6 Rxh5 32. Rf6 bxc6 33. Rxf3 Rhxh2 34. Rg3 {In this game you
should learn at least the following: 1. For Black, the start isn't very good,
looking for counterplay without development. 2. The use of the e5 square for
white. 3. White should in general advance his queen side majority as much as
he can. 4. Qc2 as a typical response to Ne4 5. The exchange Bxc6 at the
appropriate moment followed by b4. I said 'at least' because if you were able
to reach a conclusion by your own efforts, that's even better.} 1-0

