1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. c5 b6 {As I said in the
previous game: it's better to first develop and then look for counterplay. But
this move is certainly better than 6...Nc6?!} 7. b4 a5 8. Na4 $1 {The typical
response against this attempt at counterplay. White keeps his position even
with advantage. Now Black's the side that should think how to keep his
position :) . This move probably has a psychological effect on the player who
doesn't expect it.} bxc5 9. bxc5 {White obtains a protected passer.} Nfd7 10.
Nf3 Be7 11. Bf4 O-O 12. Rc1 {The player who understands this variation
understands all the last moves of both sides. It's a positional battle that
White finally won. In the last three moves Black was postponing Nc6 until
White developed his f1 bishop; and White was postponing the development of the
bishop until Black defined the Knight! Now White is threating c6, so Black
needs to stop it with 12... Nc6 - that's why I said that White won the
positional battle.} Nc6 13. Bb5 $1 {This move is typical because it avoids
Black's counterplay based on e5!} Bb7 14. O-O Bf6 15. Re1 {Controlling even
more the important e5 square.} Rc8 16. Bf1 $5 {An interesting move. White
already has an advantage and this move is a direct attempt for White. An
important thing you should take note of is that the bishop on f4 plays a very
important job, which is to control the b8 square and avoid Black's rook being
placed on the open "b" file. That's why White moves his bishop from this file
to start using it with the heavy pieces.} Ne7 17. Qb3 {White starting to use
the "b" file.} Bc6 18. Nb6 $1 {A typical strategy - look at White's perfect
coordination! The knight on b6 is trapping Black's c8 rook in combination with
the f4 bishop, and if Black exchanges it Whites obtains a "b" passer that,
combined with the f4 bishop, gives him a clear advantage.} Nxb6 19. cxb6 Qd7 {
Black should prevent b7.} 20. Ba6 {Threatening b7.} Bb7 21. Bb5 {Attacking the
queen.} Bc6 (21... Qd8 22. Bc7 $1 {Definitely this bishop deserves a medal of
honour for this game! And in general, it's a very important piece in this
variation.}) 22. Bxc6 Nxc6 23. b7 {Now White's advantage is completely
decisive.} Rcd8 24. Rxc6 Qxc6 25. b8=Q Rxb8 26. Bxb8 a4 27. Qb1 {What we
should learn at least from this game: 1. As we already know, Black's direct
attempts at counterplay aren't very effective. 2. The strategic fight in the
moves 9-12: Black's waiting to play Nc6 for White to define his f1 bishop in a
square different than b5 and finally White won the strategic battle because he
forced Black to play Nc6 first. 3. You should look at Whites Bf1!? and all the
strategy that follows. 4. You should start feeling the strength of the bishop
on f4.5. The importance of the "b" file. 6. How to use the b6 square to create
a more dangerous passer that, combined with the f4 bishop, gives White a
decisive advantage. 7. The tactical motifs of trapping Black's pieces in the
variation - 21...Qd8 22. Bc7! and also after 18.Nb6! Black's rook is trapped;
this gives White a clear-cut advantage because it forces Black to allow the
"b" passer.} 1-0

