1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 {We reach the position from a different
move order.} Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. c5 Be7 $1 {The best move for Black; he wants to
castle first and then look for counterplay.} 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Qc2 $1 {A very
important move. In this particular line, if White prevents all Black's
attempts at counterplay, or at least if not prevent it prepare a good reply
against it, this guarantees a good game for White. You already know what the
typical methods of counterplay are. And the idea of this move is to prevent
Ne4, and prepares good replies to b6 and Nc6.} b6 (8... Nc6 9. Bb5 $1 {Of
course!}) 9. b4 Bb7 $5 {Against a5 White should play 10. Na4! The typical
response!} 10. Rb1 $1 {A very important and typical prophylactic move. After 9.
. .Bb7 Black's threat of 10...a5! gains force. That's why White is PREVENTING
HIS OPPONENT'S COUNTERPLAY! against 10... a5 now White simply has 11.a3!} Nc6
11. Bd3 (11. Bb5 $1 {Is of course more logical. Anyway this game is very
instructive.}) 11... Rc8 12. O-O Ne4 {Sacrificing a pawn in the look for
counterplay. This variation is really funny to play as White, for the
following reason: you are simply waiting and placing your pieces to prevent
your opponent's counterplay, while Black is desperately looking for something
that probably, in the end, doesn't work. You should just wait and see how your
opponent gets on - losing his last breath of active play in the pure style of
Tigran Petrosian :D . In the present game after 12...Ne4 White has clear
advantage.} 13. b5 $1 {A typical move; the idea is not just to create a passer
but also to trap Black's pieces on the queen side.} Nxd4 {A desperate-looking
attempt, but also necessary.} (13... Na5 14. c6 Bxc6 15. bxc6 Rxc6 16. Bd2 $16)
14. Nxd4 Nxc3 15. Bxh7+ $1 {Whites gives back the piece to obtain a decisive
positional advantage WITH NO COUNTERPLAY FOR BLACK!} Kh8 16. Qxc3 Kxh7 17. c6
$1 {The typical idea. Now White's strategy is based on Capablanca's iron
principle: when you trap an opponent's piece on one side of the board, you
should attack on the other side, because on that side you will have a piece
up! So now just look how GM Evgeny Postny gives a masterclass.} Kg8 18. Qh3 Ba8
19. Rb3 Bf6 20. Qg4 Re8 21. Rh3 $1 {Capablanca was a very wise man.} Bxd4 22.
Qxd4 e5 23. Qd3 e4 24. Qd4 Qd6 25. Rh5 Red8 26. Rd1 Bxc6 {What else?} 27. bxc6
Rxc6 28. Bb2 f6 29. Rxd5 Qxd5 30. Qxd5+ Rxd5 31. Rxd5 Rc2 32. Rb5 {What you
should learn at least from this game: 1. The idea of preventing your
opponent's counterplay (8. Qc2; 10. Rb1). 2. The idea of trapping Black's
pieces on the queen side ( 13.b5!; 17. c6!). 3. And finally, how to take
advantage of the fact that Black's pieces, or one Black piece, are trapped on
the queen side - using Capablanca's iron principle.} 1-0

