1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. c5 Be7 7. Nf3 {Simply
developing a piece to its most active square.} O-O 8. Qc2 $1 {We already
understand this move :)} b6 9. b4 bxc5 10. bxc5 Nc6 11. Bb5 {Automatic!} Bb7
12. O-O Rc8 13. Bf4 {The 'Super Bishop'!} Qa5 14. Bxc6 {A move that sooner or
later White should make anyway.} Bxc6 15. Rab1 {Now it's time to evaluate the
position: Black has bishop pair while White has the open "b" file, a protected
passer, a super bishop on f4 and good squares for his knights, especially e5
that is one typical square for the "f3" knight in this variation.} Rfd8 16. Ne5
$14 {White's advantage is clear.} Be8 {We have a clear positional advantage,
so it's time to create a plan. White should without any doubt make use of his
passer, but one weakness is not enough - White should create another to
stretch Black's defence. So the plan is to attack on the king side and, at the
same time, use the passer.} 17. Bd2 Qa6 18. Bg5 {Pinning the knight. And
tempting Black to weaken his king side.} h6 19. Bh4 Rb8 $6 (19... g5 $1 {Risky,
but the right decision. Black shouldn't just wait.} 20. Bg3 Ne4 $1 21. Nxe4
dxe4 22. Qxe4 f5 23. Qe3 Qxa2 (23... f4 24. Bxf4 gxf4 25. Qxf4 {With attack
for White.}) 24. Ra1 Qd5 25. Rxa7 $14 {With just a slight advantage for White.}
) 20. f4 $1 {Starting the attack on the king side and preventing g5.} Qa5 21.
Qd3 (21. f5 {White should be careful about Black's resources.} Bxc5 $1 {
Typical resource in this variation.} 22. dxc5 Qxc5+ 23. Kh1 Rxb1 24. Rxb1 d4
$15) 21... Rdc8 {Threatening the same resource.} 22. Bf2 $1 Nd7 23. Rxb8 $1
Nxb8 24. f5 $1 {Now it's time to realise our plan! After this, look how Whites
plays, first creating pressure on the king side and then just pushing his
passer.} Nd7 25. Nf3 Nf8 (25... Nxc5 $1 26. dxc5 Bxc5 {Was an interesting
attempt}) 26. Re1 Bc6 27. g4 Rb8 28. Be3 $6 (28. Ne5 $1 {More logical and
better.}) 28... Qd8 29. Re2 exf5 30. Ne5 Be8 31. gxf5 Nh7 32. Rg2 {White put
his pieces looking at the king side.} Kh8 33. Bf4 Rb4 34. c6 $1 {Now it's time
to use the passer!} Qa5 35. c7 $1 {And the game is over. What we should learn
at least from this game: 1. The plan of White's attack on the king side to
distract Black's pieces. 2. Black should do something, not just wait. 3. White
should be careful about the sacrifice on c5!? (very important).} 1-0

