1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. c5 Be7 7. Qc2 {A
different move order to reach the same position anyway; I prefer 7.Nf3 because
it's more flexible.} O-O 8. Nf3 b6 9. b4 a5 10. Na4 $1 axb4 11. Nxb6 Ra5 {Now
the first critical position! You may think the following: the knight on b6 is
very strong, so I will never exchange it for the c8 bishop! This is the WRONG
thinking. The knight on b6 is temporarily strong, but in a few moves Black
will reject it or exchange it by playing Bb7 and Nfd7, for example. So it's
better to take advantage of his temporarily active position and get a stable
factor - which is the bishop pair!} 12. Nxc8 $1 (12. Bd3 Ba6 $1 {Even better
than Bb7.} 13. O-O Bxd3 14. Qxd3 Nc6 {No problems for Black here. The b6
knight does nothing.}) 12... Qxc8 13. Bd3 Nc6 14. Bf4 Qb7 15. O-O {The main
opening tasks are finished and it's time to evaluate the position. White first
of all has a bishop pair and a protected passer, and Black has a weak pawn on
b4 while White has a weak pawn on a2. So the plans are determined: each side
should attack the weak pawn of the other side. Of course, White has more
possibilities because of his other advantages.} Rfa8 16. Rfb1 {Logical moves.}
Qa7 17. Rb2 g6 18. Qe2 $1 {Threatening Bb5.} Qb7 (18... Ra3 $1 {Fixing the
weaknesses was better!} 19. Bb5 $6 Rxf3 $1 20. Qxf3 Nxd4 $17) 19. Rd1 R8a7 20.
h3 {Both sides are making slow positional manoeuvres. White is maintaining his
slight advantage.} Nd7 21. h4 $6 {Allows e5, a typical break in this variation.
} Bf6 $6 (21... e5 $1 22. Bxe5 Ndxe5 23. dxe5 Rxc5 24. h5 Bf8 $11) 22. Bb1 {
Preventing e5 and defending the weak a2 pawn.} Qa6 23. Bd3 Qb7 24. Bb1 Qa6 25.
Bd3 Qc8 {Black wrongly avoids the repetition of moves. White now enjoys even
more advantage.} 26. Bb5 h5 $2 {A move that no make sense - Black should play
on the queen side, where the main battle is! After this White wins the b4 pawn
and with that the game.} 27. Rdd2 $1 Bg7 28. Bxc6 Qxc6 29. Rxb4 Ra8 30. Rdb2
Ra4 31. Bd6 Bf6 32. Rxa4 Qxa4 33. Qc2 Qc6 34. Qb3 $18 e5 35. dxe5 Bg7 36. Qb7
Rc8 37. Qxc6 Rxc6 38. Rb5 Ra6 39. Rb7 Nxc5 {What you should learn at least
from this game: 1. The concept of the move Nxc8 - exchanging a temporary
factor for a permanent one. 2. The plans of this particular pawn structure. 3.
Always be careful about the e5 break. 4. White's slow but precise manoeuvres.
Ok, with that we finish the model games. I hope you get all the most important
ideas of this variation.} 1-0

